Africa
---
[1] Sierra Leone
Date: Fri 29 May 2015
Source: APA [edited]
http://en.starafrica.com/news/sleone-confirms-measles-outbreak.html


Health authorities in Sierra Leone`s Kono district have confirmed an outbreak of Measles in the area. According to reports Thursday [28 May 2015], the World Health Organization has dispatched emergency support and have engaged local health personnel in training to face a new threat mostly dangerous to children. The viral disease starts with fever, running nose and cough, with the patient`s eyes getting red and soon suffers sore throat.

Kono was declared a "Measles-Positive District" following test of 21 samples which returned 5 positive cases, said Sahr Amara Moiba, Kono District Disease Surveillance Officer, Ministry of Health and Sanitation (MoHS). He said the tests were carried out at the Central Reference Laboratory in Freetown. Moiba said the disease was confirmed in 7 out of 14 chiefdoms in the district: Fiama, Nimikoro, Nimiyama, Gorama Kono, Sandor, Tankoro and Gbense. 98 percent of the cases are children under 1 year of age, he added.

Hundreds of health workers from 84 Peripheral Health Units (PHUs) in the 14 chiefdoms of the district have been trained on treating the sickness, he disclosed. But that training, according Moiba, was also designed to prepare for the forthcoming national vaccination exercise for children against the measles virus, scheduled for 5 and 10 Jun 2015.

